<statement>
<p>Graph the parabola <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}+{3}\right)}^{{2}}+{2}</m></p>
<p>The vertex is <fillin characters="7" /> Â </p>
<image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/3591692cf3d9256f1b4da47cf91f5e54.png" />


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{3},{2}\right)}</m></li><li><image width="52%"  pi:generated="problems/images/3512fd40a70b353f3743dde5a41e1a12.png" />
</li></ul></p><p>The form of a parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}={a}{\left({x}-{h}\right)}^{{2}}+{k}</m>. Because this parabola is <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}+{3}\right)}^{{2}}+{2}</m>, which can be written <m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left({x}-{\left(-{3}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({2}\right)}</m> we know the following.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{h}=-{3}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{k}={2}</m>. Thus the vertex is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{3},{2}\right)}</m>.</p>
<p>To graph the parabola we can use the vertex and another convenient point. One convenient point is at <m>\displaystyle{x}=-{3}+{1}=-{2}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={6}{\left(-{2}-{\left(-{3}\right)}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({2}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={6}{\left({1}\right)}^{{2}}+{\left({2}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={6}+{\left({2}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle={8}</m>.</p>
<p>We use <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{2},{8}\right)}</m>.</p>
</solution>
